#* '''1991''', Edward Johnson, ''The Handbook of Good English'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=n0IJ8GcdJ6IC&pg=PA208&dq=%22gerund%22%7C%22gerunds%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nQwEVMTaM4Lg8AWPloCADA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22gerund%22%7C%22gerunds%22&f=false page 208],
#*: Compounds in which '''gerunds''' are the second element look exactly like compounds in which present participles are the second element, but different principles of hyphenation apply.
#* '''2002''', Dan Mulvey, ''Grammar the Easy Way'', [http://books.google.com.au/books?id=L9ni2hGHlMEC&pg=PA25&dq=%22gerund%22%7C%22gerunds%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nQwEVMTaM4Lg8AWPloCADA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22gerund%22%7C%22gerunds%22&f=false page 25],
#*: Like any noun, the '''gerund''' functions as a subject, direct object, indirect object, object of the preposition, or predicate nominative. The '''gerund''' phrase is made up of the present participle ("-ing") and can contain an object and/or a modifier (and sometimes many modifiers). The '''gerund''' is a verbal noun.
#* '''2005''', Gary Lutz, Diane Stevenson, ''The Writer's Digest Grammar Desk Reference'', [https://web.archive.org/web/20160917095905/https://books.google.com.au/books?id=SsQ9ugnMcpUC&pg=PA55&dq=%22gerund%22%7C%22gerunds%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=nQwEVMTaM4Lg8AWPloCADA&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=%22gerund%22%7C%22gerunds%22&f=false page 55],
#*: '''Gerunds''' and '''gerund''' phrases are always nouns, so they are always predicate nominatives when used as complements. Do be careful to distinguish progressive-tense verbs from '''gerunds''' used as subjective complements.
# {{lb|en|grammar}} In some languages such as [[Dutch]], [[Italian]] or [[Russian]], a verbal form similar to a [[present participle]], but [[function]]ing as an [[adverb]] to form [[adverbial phrase]]s or continuous tense. These constructions have various names besides ''gerund'', depending on the language, such as ''[[conjunctive]] [[participle]]s, [[active participle]]s,  [[adverbial participle]]s, [[transgressive]]s,'' etc.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2013|isbn=978-1444137699|edition=Kindle|title=A New Reference Grammar of Modern Spanish|author=John Butt|publisher=Routledge|author2=Carmen Benjamin|passage=The Spanish '''gerund''' is quite unlike the English -ing form (‘walking’, ‘replying’, ‘saying’, etc.), which can function as a gerund, a present participle, a noun or an adjective; and it is also unlike the French form ending in ''-ant'', which covers the functions of both the Spanish '''gerund''' and the adjectival form in ''-ante'', ''-(i)ente'' discussed at 19.4.}}

